## Preliminary Testing
*   Finished integrating APB to I2C controller module on port 9 of the apb mux in cmsdk\_apb\_subsystem.v
*   Speaking with Archisman, there are some constraints that were considered for the eventual porting to the asic flow where the bidirectional sda has been broken into sda\_i and sda\_o
*   Obviously, i2c only has one sda line, I need to do some additional conditioning on the sda\_i and sda\_o signals in my testing, as well as develop an i2c slave.
*   Here is the current **_i2c\_bus\_buffer.v_** file that I've created:

```verilog
// ==============================================================================
// I2C Bus Interface Buffer Module (Tri-state/Open-Drain Modeling)
// This module bridges the three-signal I2C output style (sda_o, sda_i, oe)
// used by the APB Master to a single bidirectional 'inout' port (sda_bidir)
// required by the I2C Slave/Testbench environment.
// ==============================================================================
module i2c_bus_buffer (
    // Signals from the I2C Master (APB Controller)
    input  wire sda_o,     // Data to drive onto the bus (D). For I2C open-drain,
                           // this should be 0 when driving and 1 when not driving.
    output wire sda_i,     // Data read from the bus (Q)
    input  wire oe,        // Output Enable. Polarity controlled by parameter.

    // Bidirectional Bus Connection (Connected to the Slave 'inout')
    inout  wire sda_bidir  // The actual I2C data line (pad / testbench net)
);

// assign sda_bidir = ~oe ? sda_o : 1'bz;
// Defensive assignment: only drive low when oe is asserted and sda_o is 0, otherwise high-Z
assign sda_bidir = ((oe === 1'b0) && (sda_o === 1'b0))  ? 1'b0 :
                                    (oe == 1'b1)        ? sda_o : 1'bz;

// Reading the bus: the master's input observes the actual state of the pad.
assign sda_i = sda_bidir;
// assign sda_i = (oe == 1'b1) ? ~sda_bidir : 1'b0; (test later)

endmodule


```

*   Here is the current i2c slave that's also been instantiated in the testbench:

```verilog
// ==============================================================================
// Simple I2C Slave Module
// - Responds to a fixed 7-bit slave address (ADDR_SLAVE).
// - Provides a small 8-register memory space for Read/Write transactions.
// - Uses a single bidirectional 'sda' port.
// ==============================================================================
module I2Cslave (
    input  wire CLK,       // System Clock (must be much faster than SCL)
    input  wire RST_n,     // Asynchronous Reset (Active Low)

    inout  wire sda,       // Bidirectional I2C Data line (connected via buffer)
    input  wire scl        // I2C Clock line (from Master)
);

// ==========================================================================
// Parameters and Local Wires/Registers
// ==========================================================================

localparam ADDR_SLAVE = 7'h42; // Example 7-bit slave address (0x84/0x85 for R/W)
localparam REG_ADDR_WIDTH = 3;  // 8 registers (0 to 7)

// Internal Register File (8 x 8-bit registers)
reg [7:0] registers [0:((1 << REG_ADDR_WIDTH) - 1)];
reg [REG_ADDR_WIDTH-1:0] reg_addr; // Internal register address pointer

// FSM States
localparam [3:0]
    IDLE            = 4'h0,
    START_DETECT    = 4'h1,
    ADDR_RX         = 4'h2,
    ADDR_ACK        = 4'h3,
    DATA_RX         = 4'h4,
    DATA_ACK_TX     = 4'h5,
    DATA_TX         = 4'h6,
    DATA_ACK_RX     = 4'h7,
    STOP_DETECT     = 4'h8;

reg [3:0] state, next_state;
reg [3:0] bit_count;

reg sda_i_prev;
wire start, stop;

// SCL Synchronization (Detecting I2C Clock Edges)
reg scl_d1, scl_d2;
wire scl_rising_edge;
wire scl_falling_edge;

// Data Shift Registers
reg [7:0] shift_reg_rx; // Incoming data
reg [7:0] shift_reg_tx; // Outgoing data

// Output Control
reg sda_o;      // Data to drive onto the bus (0 when asserting ACK/Data)
reg oe;         // Output Enable (Active High - drives 0 onto SDA)
wire sda_i;     // Data read from the bus

// ==========================================================================
// I2C Bus Interface Logic
// ==========================================================================

// 1. Read the bus state
assign sda_i = sda;

// 2. Drive the bus (Open-Drain Modeling)
// When oe is high, the slave is pulling sda low (sda_o must be 0)
assign sda = (oe == 1'b1) ? sda_o : 1'bz;

assign start = (scl & ~sda_i & sda_i_prev);
assign stop  = (scl & sda_i & ~sda_i_prev);

// ==========================================================================
// I2C Clock Edge Detection (Synchronous to CLK)
// ==========================================================================

always @(posedge CLK or negedge RST_n) begin
    if (!RST_n) begin
        scl_d1 <= 1'b1; // Initialize high to avoid spurious edge at reset
        scl_d2 <= 1'b1;
    end else begin
        scl_d1 <= scl;
        scl_d2 <= scl_d1;
    end
end

// Rising edge detection (when data is sampled/shifted)
assign scl_rising_edge = scl_d1 & (~scl_d2);
// Falling edge detection (when data is driven)
assign scl_falling_edge = (~scl_d1) & scl_d2;

// ==========================================================================
// Register File Initialization (Optional: for simulation clarity)
// ==========================================================================

integer i;
initial begin
    for (i = 0; i < (1 << REG_ADDR_WIDTH); i = i + 1) begin
        registers[i] = 8'hAA; // Default values
    end
end

// ==========================================================================
// State Register
// ==========================================================================

always @(posedge CLK or negedge RST_n) begin
    if (!RST_n)
        state <= IDLE;
    else
        state <= next_state;
end

always @(posedge CLK or negedge RST_n) begin
    if (!RST_n)
        sda_i_prev <= 1'b1; // Initialize high
    else
        sda_i_prev <= sda_i;
end

// ==========================================================================
// State Machine Next State Logic
// ==========================================================================

always @(*) begin
    next_state = state;
    // Default to tri-state/release
    sda_o = 1'b1; // Drive '1' if tri-state is required (i.e., not driving 0)
    oe = 1'b0;    // Default: High-Z (allowing bus to float high)

    case (state)
        IDLE: begin
            // Wait for a START condition: SDA goes low while SCL is high
            if (start)
                next_state = START_DETECT;
            else
                next_state = IDLE;
        end

        START_DETECT: begin
            // Wait for SCL to go low (end of START condition)
            if (scl == 1'b0)
                next_state = ADDR_RX;
        end

        ADDR_RX: begin
            // Receive 8 bits (7-bit address + R/W bit)
            if (scl_rising_edge) begin
                if (bit_count == 4'd7) // R/W bit
                    next_state = ADDR_ACK;
                else
                    next_state = ADDR_RX;
            end
        end

        ADDR_ACK: begin
            // Address matched. Send ACK (drive SDA low for 9th clock pulse)
            oe = 1'b1; // Drive bus
            sda_o = 1'b0; // Drive low (ACK)

            if (scl_rising_edge) begin
                // Check R/W bit received in bit 7 of shift_reg_rx
                if (shift_reg_rx[0] == 1'b0) // Read operation (R/W=0)
                    next_state = DATA_TX;
                else                         // Write operation (R/W=1)
                    bit_count = 4'd0;
                    next_state = DATA_RX;
            end else if (scl == 1'b1 && sda_i == 1'b1 && bit_count == 4'd8) begin
                // No match or NACK logic (in this simple slave, we only ACK our address)
                if (shift_reg_rx[7:1] != ADDR_SLAVE) begin
                    next_state = IDLE; // If address doesn't match, return to IDLE
                end
            end
        end

        // --- MASTER WRITE PATH ---
        DATA_RX: begin
            // Receiving 8 data bits (SCL rising edge)
            if (scl_rising_edge) begin
                if (bit_count == 4'd7)
                    next_state = DATA_ACK_TX;
                else
                    next_state = DATA_RX;
            end
            // Check for STOP condition (SDA goes high while SCL is high)
            else if (stop)
                next_state = STOP_DETECT;
        end

        DATA_ACK_TX: begin
            // Send ACK (drive SDA low for 9th clock pulse)
            oe = 1'b1;
            sda_o = 1'b0; // ACK

            if (scl_rising_edge) begin
                bit_count = 4'd0;
                next_state = DATA_RX; // Expecting next data byte
            end
            else if (stop)
                next_state = STOP_DETECT;
        end

        // --- MASTER READ PATH ---
        DATA_TX: begin
            // Sending 8 data bits (SCL falling edge prepares data)
            // Data is driven on SCL falling edge and released on SCL rising edge
            if (scl_falling_edge) begin
                oe = 1'b1;
                sda_o = shift_reg_tx[7-bit_count]; // Drive data
            end else if (scl_rising_edge) begin
                oe = 1'b0; // Release bus

                if (bit_count == 4'd7)
                    next_state = DATA_ACK_RX;
                else
                    next_state = DATA_TX;
            end
        end

        DATA_ACK_RX: begin
            // Master sends ACK/NACK (SDA sampled on SCL rising edge)
            // Slave releases bus (oe=0)
            if (scl_rising_edge) begin
                if (sda_i == 1'b0) // Master sends ACK
                    next_state = DATA_TX;
                else // Master sends NACK or STOP
                    next_state = STOP_DETECT;
            end
        end

        STOP_DETECT: begin
            // Wait for SCL to go low then high, and SDA to go high (STOP condition)
            if (~scl)
                next_state = IDLE; // Reset FSM
        end

        default: next_state = IDLE;
    endcase
end

// ==========================================================================
// I2C Data and Bit Counter Logic (Synchronous to CLK)
// ==========================================================================

always @(posedge CLK or negedge RST_n) begin
    if (!RST_n) begin
        bit_count <= 4'h0;
        reg_addr <= 3'h0;
        shift_reg_rx <= 8'h00;
    end else begin
        // Bit Counter Logic
        if (scl_rising_edge && (state == ADDR_RX || state == DATA_RX || state == DATA_TX))
            bit_count <= bit_count + 4'h1;
        else if (state == IDLE || state == STOP_DETECT || (scl_rising_edge && bit_count == 4'd7))
            bit_count <= 4'h0;


        // Data Shift and Sample Logic (SCL Rising Edge)
        if (scl_rising_edge) begin
            case (state)
                ADDR_RX: begin
                    // Shift in the 7-bit address and R/W bit (MSB first)
                    shift_reg_rx <= {shift_reg_rx[6:0], sda_i};
                end

                ADDR_ACK: begin
                    // If address matches (R/W=0), the first received byte is the internal register address.
                    if (shift_reg_rx[7:1] == ADDR_SLAVE && shift_reg_rx[0] == 1'b0)
                        reg_addr <= shift_reg_rx[REG_ADDR_WIDTH+3:4]; // Example: bits 4:1 of 8-bit received word
                    // Prepare data for transmission if R/W=1
                    else if (shift_reg_rx[7:1] == ADDR_SLAVE && shift_reg_rx[0] == 1'b1)
                        shift_reg_tx <= registers[reg_addr];
                end

                DATA_RX: begin
                    // Shift in data bytes
                    shift_reg_rx <= {shift_reg_rx[6:0], sda_i};
                end

                DATA_ACK_TX: begin
                    // Write received data to the register file and advance register address
                    registers[reg_addr] <= shift_reg_rx;
                    reg_addr <= reg_addr + 3'h1; // Auto-increment address
                end

                DATA_TX: begin
                    // Data transmission logic (shift out)
                    // Note: Data preparation happens in DATA_ACK_RX/ADDR_ACK
                end

                DATA_ACK_RX: begin
                    // If Master sends ACK (sda_i=0), prepare next byte for transmission
                    if (sda_i == 1'b0) begin
                        reg_addr <= reg_addr + 3'h1; // Auto-increment address
                        shift_reg_tx <= registers[reg_addr]; // Pre-fetch next byte
                    end
                end
            endcase
        end
    end
end
endmodule
```

*   **Current Testing Status**:
    *   i2c writes have been validated at standard 100KHz and i2c fast mode at 400KHz
        *   Single and multi-byte writes
    *   Revised i2c slave model to read first data byte as internal slave register
*   **December 5, 2025**
    *   I was able to add additional states in the master controller as well as the behavioural slave to account for writing to particular internal slave registers, following the read and write transaction for the i2c standard:
    ![](https://t9017196379.p.clickup-attachments.com/t9017196379/2a96a572-48fd-4920-9adb-891ab8ac66fa/image.png)
![](https://t9017196379.p.clickup-attachments.com/t9017196379/61be44f6-92eb-466a-a4c2-e1058aa552da/image.png)
*       *   So I implemented things up to the point where a tx buffer on the slave side was loaded with the contents of one of it's internal registers based on an 8-bit transmitted Register Address N that follows the 7-bit Device (Slave) Address
    *   The next stage was to transmit this onto the sda line to be received by the master
    *   However in debugging this step, a critical error was revealed that I'd intentionally "masked" in validating write transactions.
    *   Essentially in my buffer that muxes the two single-ended sda\_o and sda\_i from the master controller into a bidirectional sda (inout port), it looks like my implementation ignored an error from the master controller, where sda data was still being sent to the slave via sda\_o despite releasing output enable
    *   Error in my buffer implementation:

```verilog
assign sda_bidir = ((oe === 1'b0) && (sda_o === 1'b0))  ? 1'b0 :
                                    (oe == 1'b1)        ? sda_o : 1'bz;

// Reading the bus: the master's input observes the actual state of the pad.
assign sda_i = sda_bidir;
// assign sda_i = (oe == 1'b1) ? ~sda_bidir : 1'b0; (test later)
```

*       *   The case where oe == 1'b1 should not be considered as this case indicates to the slave device that it can transmit data
    *   The correct implementation is this:

```verilog
assign sda_bidir = ~oe ? sda_o : 1'bz;

// Reading the bus: the master's input observes the actual state of the pad.
assign sda_i = (oe == 1'b1) ? ~sda_bidir : 1'b0;
```

where sda\_bidir is pulled up in high-impedance cases
*       *   So there is an issue on the master side where sda\_o still drives valid data when oe is released, I'll have to look into this to fully validate the read and write transactions.
    *   **December 8, 2025**
        *   After modifying the buffer I did some more debugging in my behvioural slave model and master controller side.
        *   I'm now able to run basic read and write transactions from an i2c slave device
        *   Will have to test the accuracy of the status flags by triggering them on purpose and multi byte transfers
## I2C Read Transaction (Dec. 16, 2025)
![](https://t9017196379.p.clickup-attachments.com/t9017196379/9e762868-5979-43e3-9393-26c257c22623/image.png)
*   The following diagram above details the current status of i2c read transaction testing
*   In the internal registers of the i2c slave model, there is a value "67" located at address location "0x3"
*   Looking at the state variables of the slave and master models:

```verilog
  // ============================================================================
  // State Machine Encoding (Master)
  // ============================================================================

  localparam IDLE             = 4'd0;
  localparam ADDRESS_SEND     = 4'd1;
  localparam ADDRESS_ACK_WAIT = 4'd2;
  localparam DATA_SEND        = 4'd3;
  localparam DATA_ACK_WAIT    = 4'd4;
  localparam DATA_RECEIVE     = 4'd5;
  localparam DATA_RECEIVE_ACK = 4'd6;
  localparam DONE             = 4'd7;
  localparam WAIT_TX_DATA     = 4'd8;

  localparam DATA_SEND_REGADDR = 4'd9;
  localparam DATA_REG_ACK_WAIT = 4'd10;

  // ============================================================================
  // State Machine Encoding (Master)
  // ============================================================================
localparam [3:0]
    IDLE            = 4'h0,
    START_DETECT    = 4'h1,
    ADDR_RX         = 4'h2,
    ADDR_ACK        = 4'h3,
    DATA_RX         = 4'h4,
    DATA_ACK_TX     = 4'h5,
    DATA_TX         = 4'h6,
    DATA_ACK_RX     = 4'h7,
    STOP_DETECT     = 4'h8;
```

### Current Issues
*   **Addressable Internal i2c master registers**
    *   While the value is present on the APB bus, there is no clear way of accessing the value via an address
        *   **Solution**: Adding an internal data registers, which reg\_rx\_buf seems to be, but making it addressable will allow the user application to obtain the data in some location in SRAM.
*   **2 bus conflicts**
    *   There is some bus conflict at 690us on the sda line for the second ACK from the slave, but this does not appear to disrupt the master's process, but this needs to be debugged.
        *   **Solution:** In debugging this, I found the bus conflict was due to some error in my i2c slave implementation where I was driving the sda\_o from the slave in two locations
    *   And another bus conflict at 710us where the master sends an ACK once the data from the slave has been received, this is likely why the slave never properly terminates.
        *   **Solution:** This again doesn't have to do with the ACK, but the temporary bus conflict has to do with a slight misalignment in my i2c slave model's state transition and the i2c master controller.
        *   So this is acceptable as a likely better implementation of the behavioural slave might not show this, but as it is momentary the misalingment doesn't affect the state transitions.
    *   In general, it's important to note that ACK's in i2c transactions are transmitted by pulling the sda line low so this means the acknowlodgements from both the slave and master are transmitted properly seeing as the state transitions do progress forward.
*   **Termination of i2c slave**
    *   **Solution:** Once the done signal has been received from the master, there was an error in my slave model from transitioning from the DATA\_ACK\_RX state once data has been read by master to the STOP\_DETECT state.
    *   I fixed this and the slave transitioned to IDLE successfully. Next is to test multi-byte writes
