## Conclusion
*   The testing of this peripheral was a lot more involved as it demanded on a very reliable i2c slave model
*   Most of the debug was work on refining the slave model and revising the master controller when appropriate
    *   So this meant adding more registers (i.e. dedicated status register for polling the state of the master, an addressable buffer to read the rx\_data on the APB bus, etc.)
*   Ultimately, the implementation of the controller does not account for transactions outside the initial testbench between the **memory** → APB → i2c controller → APB → core → i2c slave → core → APB → **i2c controller** which posed more challenges than simply simulating an apb\_write or apb\_read transaction in the testbench
    *   So transactions between the user memory (RAM/ROM), external application code
*   The tests in the i2c test suite have some limits. These limits are due to the relatively simple behavioural model of my i2c slave and not to do with the master controller.
*   All read/write transaction tests, inclduing single and burst transactions can be run at once
*   The status flag tests must be run once per test run
    *   There is some issue with some state transition logic in my behavioural slave where my model does not stay at IDLE once a nack has been received or cleared. So this would affect the following test
*   From the status flag tests above, this was a result of running them individually
